<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-pointestimates" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Estimating population parameters</title>
    <p>
        In the previous sections, we used examples where the population parameters were already known. 
        This allowed us to focus on the ideas of sampling, sampling distributions, and the behaviour of sample statistics. 
        In practice, however, the values of population parameters are rarely known. 
        Instead, the goal of statistical inference is to use information from a sample to estimate these unknown quantities.
    </p>
    <p>
        Suppose you are interested in estimating the average income of households in a county, the average crop yield from a farming region, 
        or the proportion of patients who recover after receiving a particular treatment. 
        It is usually impractical or impossible to collect data from every member of the population. 
        Instead, a sample is selected, and statistics calculated from that sample are used to estimate the corresponding population parameters.
    </p>
    <p>
        This process of using sample information to estimate unknown population characteristics is called
        <em>statistical estimation</em>. Because different samples produce different sample statistics, every estimate is subject to sampling variation. 
        Understanding this variability is essential when interpreting estimates and assessing how reliable they are.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this section, we introduce two of the most widely used approaches to estimation:
        <em>point estimation</em>, which provides a single best estimate of a population parameter, and
        <em>confidence intervals</em>, which provide a range of plausible values for the parameter.
        These methods form the foundation of statistical inference and are supported throughout the chapter using
        <em>R-Instat</em>.
    </p>

    <xi:include href="subsections/pointestimates/subsec-pop_mean-estimation.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="subsections/pointestimates/subsec-pop_sd_estimation.ptx" />

</section>